1. SECOND LARGEST NUMBER

🔹 Approach (Brute Force – Sorting)
Sort the array in ascending order
Find the maximum element (last element)
Traverse from second last element backwards
Return the first element smaller than maximum

⚠️ Edge Case
If array has less than 2 elements, return -1


💻 Code (Sorting Approach)
import java.util.Arrays;

class Solution {
    public int getSecondLargest(int[] arr) {
        int n = arr.length;
        
        if (n < 2) return -1;

        Arrays.sort(arr);
        int max = arr[n - 1];
        
        for (int i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
            if (arr[i] < max) {
                return arr[i];
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
}

⏱ Complexity
Time: O(n log n) (due to sorting)
Space: O(1)


-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
🚀 Optimal Solution (Best Approach – Single Pass)

🔹 Approach
Traverse the array once
Maintain two variables:
largest
secondLargest
Update values while iterating:
If current element > largest → update both
Else if element lies between largest and secondLargest → update secondLargest


💻 Code (Optimal Approach)
class Solution {
    public int getSecondLargest(int[] arr) {
        int largest = Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        int secondLargest = Integer.MIN_VALUE;

        for (int num : arr) {
            if (num > largest) {
                secondLargest = largest;
                largest = num;
            } 
            else if (num > secondLargest && num != largest) {
                secondLargest = num;
            }
        }

        return (secondLargest == Integer.MIN_VALUE) ? -1 : secondLargest;
    }
}

⏱ Complexity
Time: O(n) ✅
Space: O(1) ✅

🧠 Key Points
Avoid using -1 for initialization → use Integer.MIN_VALUE
Handles:
Duplicates ✔️
Negative numbers ✔️
All elements same ✔️

🎯 Conclusion
Sorting approach is simple but slower
Optimal approach is faster and preferred in interviews 💯
